SIMPLE: spoliation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spoliation
<hw>Spo`li*a"tion</hw> <pr>(sp⟦omac⟧"l⟦icr⟧*⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>spoliatio</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>spoliation</ets>. See <er>Spoil</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of plundering; robbery; deprivation;
despoliation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Legal <qex>spoliation</qex>, which will impoverish one part of the
community in order to corrupt the remainder.</q> <rj><qau>Sir G. C.
Lewis.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Robbery or plunder in war; especially, the
authorized act or practice of plundering neutrals at sea.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Eccl. Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The act of an
incumbent in taking the fruits of his benefice without right, but under
a pretended title.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A process for possession of a church in a spiritual
court.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Injury done to a
document.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spoliative</ent>⟦br⟧
